- fnmatch-p-hang: tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst hangs the testee at 100%
  CPU; not yet isolated to a specific case within the file.

    ./shish tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst

- fdtable-cycle-detection: the fdtable resolver has no real cycle
  detection, only a defensive depth cap; a genuinely cyclic
  redirection fails instead of resolving. Not yet isolated to a
  concrete repro; illustrative (unconfirmed) attempt:

    exec 3<&0
    exec 4<&3
    exec 3<&4

- quoted-at-empty-param-split: quoted "$@" silently drops empty
  positional parameters when expanded as command arguments; the same
  case in a for-loop additionally fails to *parse* rather than just
  misbehave.

    f() { test "$@"; echo $?; }
    f -n ""

    set -- -n ""
    for a in "$@"; do echo "[$a]"; done

- fd-close-noop: ">&-"/"<&-" doesn't really close a file descriptor,
  for builtins (silently redirected to a null sink) or external
  commands (fd left pointing at the shell's original target).

    exec 3>&-
    echo hi >&3

- sig-push-sigset-cast: sig_push() reinterprets sigset_t through an
  unsigned long*, UB on any ABI where sizeof(sigset_t) differs;
  currently harmless because the function is unused (dead code, not
  reachable from any shell script).

- sh-onsig-async-unsafe: sh_onsig(), the SIGCHLD handler, calls
  term_erase()/term_restore()/buffered i/o directly from signal-handler
  context; none of that is async-signal-safe. Any background job
  finishing exercises the handler, though the unsafety is a latent
  race, not a deterministic per-run failure.

    sleep 1 &
    sleep 2 &
    wait

- nested-backquote: nested backquote command substitution (inner
  backquotes escaped with backslash, per POSIX 2.6.3) doesn't work;
  the inner backquotes are left completely unprocessed.

    nested=`echo \`echo inner\``
    echo "$nested"

- printf-field-width: builtin printf doesn't support a field
  width/flags on numeric conversions -- the format string is printed
  back completely unprocessed instead of being applied. A bare
  conversion with no width works fine, and "%X" prints lowercase
  digits instead of uppercase.

    printf "%08x\n" 255

- subshell-function-body-isolation: a function defined with a
  subshell as its body ("f() ( ... )") does not actually isolate
  variable assignments into a subshell the way a bare "( ... )"
  subshell does.

    f() ( X=inner )
    X=outer
    f
    echo $X

- dash-c-for-loop-parse-error: a "for" (and likely "while"/"until")
  loop passed via "-c" fails to parse with "unexpected token EOF,
  expecting 'done'", while the exact same text parses fine as a
  script file. Found while testing export-unset-segfault; confirmed
  pre-existing on a clean checkout, not a regression.

    shish -c 'for i in a b c; do echo "[$i]"; done'

- cmdsubst-external-stderr-redirect-lost: an external command's
  "2>&1" inside a command substitution doesn't get captured -- it
  leaks straight to the shell's own real stderr instead, and the
  substitution captures nothing for it. A builtin's own error message
  (e.g. command-not-found, printed by the shell itself) *is* captured
  correctly in the same position, so this is specific to redirections
  applied to a forked external command's fds inside fd_subst()'s
  in-process sink. Found incidentally while verifying the
  quoted-cmdsubst-field-split fix; not yet investigated further.

    x=$(ls /nonexistent-dir-for-bug-repro 2>&1)
    echo "got: [$x]"

- misclassified-special-builtins: "alias", "getopts", "local", "umask",
  and "unalias" are all marked B_SPECIAL in builtin_table.c, but none
  of them are in POSIX 2.14's actual special-builtin list
  (break/colon/continue/./eval/exec/exit/export/readonly/return/set/
  shift/times/trap/unset) -- same misclassification "read" had (fixed,
  fixes/50), just not yet confirmed to cause the same degree of
  user-visible breakage for each of these. "getopts" is the most
  likely to actually matter: like "read", it sets caller-visible
  variables (OPTARG, OPTIND, the named variable), so a prefix
  assignment on it probably has the exact same "persists afterward"
  symptom "read" had. Found while fixing read-prefix-assign-leaks; not
  investigated further per builtin.

    IFS=: getopts ":a:" opt "-a" "x:y"
    echo "IFS after=[$IFS]"

- expand-glob-stack-overflow: found via an ASan build running
  tests/param.sh (which exercises heavy nested command-substitution +
  subshell use) -- a stack-buffer-overflow in
  src/expand/expand_glob.c:48. Not yet isolated to a minimal repro
  outside that test; noted here so it doesn't get lost, since the
  ASan run that found it was chasing an unrelated bug
  (fdstack-push-assertion, now fixed) that had been masking it.

    ./shish tests/param.sh   # under an ASan build
